# Literature Review: Cyber-insurance in EU policy-making: Regulatory options, the marketâ€™s challenges

and the US example

## Introduction

The increasing use of digital technologies in our daily lives has brought about numerous benefits but also
exposed us to significant cyber risks. As a result, cyber-insurance has emerged as a viable method for
transferring cyber risks. However, the effectiveness of cyber-insurance in improving network security is
contingent upon various factors, such as the interdependency of cybersecurity efforts and advances in
Internet measurement and machine learning techniques (Woods et al., 2017).

## Impact of Security Interdependency on Contract Design

The interdependent nature of cybersecurity poses challenges for insurers and insureds in designing
effective cyber-insurance contracts. Woods et al. (2017) investigate the impact of security interdependency
on the contract design problem. They demonstrate that security interdependency creates a "profit opportunity" for insurers by exploiting inefficient effort levels of interdependent agents. Insurers can design
contracts that incentivize insureds to increase their effort levels, leading to improved network security
and increased profitability for insurers.

## Role of Pre-Screening and Security Interdependence in Policy Design

Khalili et al. (2018) also explore the role of pre-screening and security interdependence in designing
cyber insurance policies. They highlight the importance of incorporating risk externalities and risk
interdependencies into the policy design process. By utilizing security pre-screening, insurers can design
contracts that encourage insureds to enhance their effort levels, resulting in improved network security
and increased profitability for insurers.

## Symbiotic Relationship between Security Vendors and Cyber-insurance Agencies

To address the profitability challenges faced by network risk management services, Pal and Golubchik
(2010) propose a symbiotic relationship between security vendors and cyber-insurance agencies. They
suggest differentiated security pricing mechanisms that allow security vendors to price differentiate their
clients based on security investment information from insurance agencies. This approach enables security
